# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dm-verity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashing is a one-directional mathematical operation which is quick to calculate, yet hard to reverse.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] So password storage and digital signatures benefit from hashes.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Even a small change in the input results in a very different hash.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] So it is useful to check if two copies of data or software match.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Typically the operation works on a block of input data; the hash output is then hashed with the next block, creating a new hash reflecting everything to that point; again and again until the final hash reflects everything through the final block.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Cryptographic hash functions have many information-security applications, notably in digital signatures, message authentication codes (MACs), and other forms of authentication.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] They can also be used as ordinary hash functions, to index data in hash tables, for fingerprinting, to detect duplicate data or uniquely identify files, and as checksums to detect accidental data corruption.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Indeed, in information-security contexts, cryptographic hash values are sometimes called (*digital*) *fingerprints*, *checksums*, (*message*) *digests*, or just *hash values*, even though all these terms stand for more general functions with rather different properties and purposes.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic hash functions are used in hash tables and to detect accidental errors; their constructions frequently provide no resistance to a deliberate attack.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a denial-of-service attack on hash tables is possible if the collisions are easy to find, as in the case of linear cyclic redundancy check (CRC) functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Most cryptographic hash functions are designed to take a string of any length as input and produce a fixed-length hash value.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A cryptographic hash function must be able to withstand all known types of cryptanalytic attack.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance implies second pre-image resistance but does not imply pre-image resistance.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The weaker assumption is always preferred in theoretical cryptography, but in practice, a hash-function that is only second pre-image resistant is considered insecure and is therefore not recommended for real applications.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Informally, these properties mean that a malicious adversary cannot replace or modify the input data without changing its digest.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Thus, if two strings have the same digest, one can be very confident that they are identical.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Second pre-image resistance prevents an attacker from crafting a document with the same hash as a document the attacker cannot control.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collision resistance prevents an attacker from creating two distinct documents with the same hash.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A function meeting these criteria may still have undesirable properties.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Currently, popular cryptographic hash functions are vulnerable to *length-extension* attacks: given hash(*m*) and len(*m*) but not *m*, by choosing a suitable *m*′ an attacker can calculate hash(*m* ∥ *m*′), where ∥ denotes concatenation.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This property can be used to break naive authentication schemes based on hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The HMAC construction works around these problems.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In practice, collision resistance is insufficient for many practical uses.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In addition to collision resistance, it should be impossible for an adversary to find two messages with substantially similar digests; or to infer any useful information about the data, given only its digest.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, a hash function should behave as much as possible like a random function (often called a random oracle in proofs of security) while still being deterministic and efficiently computable.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This rules out functions like the SWIFFT function, which can be rigorously proven to be collision-resistant assuming that certain problems on ideal lattices are computationally difficult, but, as a linear function, does not satisfy these additional properties.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Checksum algorithms, such as CRC-32 and other cyclic redundancy checks, are designed to meet much weaker requirements and are generally unsuitable as cryptographic hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, a CRC was used for message integrity in the WEP encryption standard, but an attack was readily discovered, which exploited the linearity of the checksum.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In cryptographic practice, "difficult" generally means "almost certainly beyond the reach of any adversary who must be prevented from breaking the system for as long as the security of the system is deemed important".
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The meaning of the term is therefore somewhat dependent on the application since the effort that a malicious agent may put into the task is usually proportional to their expected gain.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, since the needed effort usually multiplies with the digest length, even a thousand-fold advantage in processing power can be neutralized by adding a dozen bits to the latter.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For messages selected from a limited set of messages, for example passwords or other short messages, it can be feasible to invert a hash by trying all possible messages in the set.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Because cryptographic hash functions are typically designed to be computed quickly, special key derivation functions that require greater computing resources have been developed that make such brute-force attacks more difficult.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In some theoretical analyses "difficult" has a specific mathematical meaning, such as "not solvable in asymptotic polynomial time".
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Such interpretations of *difficulty* are important in the study of provably secure cryptographic hash functions but do not usually have a strong connection to practical security.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, an exponential-time algorithm can sometimes still be fast enough to make a feasible attack.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Conversely, a polynomial-time algorithm (e.g., one that requires *n*20 steps for *n*-digit keys) may be too slow for any practical use.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] An illustration of the potential use of a cryptographic hash is as follows: Alice poses a tough math problem to Bob and claims that she has solved it.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Bob would like to try it himself, but would yet like to be sure that Alice is not bluffing.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Therefore, Alice writes down her solution, computes its hash, and tells Bob the hash value (whilst keeping the solution secret).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Then, when Bob comes up with the solution himself a few days later, Alice can prove that she had the solution earlier by revealing it and having Bob hash it and then check that it matches the hash value given to him before.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] An important application of secure hashes is the verification of message integrity.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Comparing message digests (hash digests over the message) calculated before, and after, transmission can determine whether any changes have been made to the message or file.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5, SHA-1, or SHA-2 hash digests are sometimes published on websites or forums to allow verification of integrity for downloaded files, including files retrieved using file sharing such as mirroring.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This practice establishes a chain of trust as long as the hashes are posted on a trusted site – usually the originating site – authenticated by HTTPS.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Using a cryptographic hash and a chain of trust detects malicious changes to the file.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Non-cryptographic error-detecting codes such as cyclic redundancy checks only prevent against *non-malicious* alterations of the file, since an intentional spoof can readily be crafted to have the colliding code value.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Almost all digital signature schemes require a cryptographic hash to be calculated over the message.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This allows the signature calculation to be performed on the relatively small, statically sized hash digest.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The message is considered authentic if the signature verification succeeds given the signature and recalculated hash digest over the message.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] So the message integrity property of the cryptographic hash is used to create secure and efficient digital signature schemes.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Password verification commonly relies on cryptographic hashes.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Storing all user passwords as cleartext can result in a massive security breach if the password file is compromised.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] One way to reduce this danger is to only store the hash digest of each password.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] To authenticate a user, the password presented by the user is hashed and compared with the stored hash.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A password reset method is required when password hashing is performed; original passwords cannot be recalculated from the stored hash value.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, use of standard cryptographic hash functions, such as the SHA series, is no longer considered safe for password storage.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] These algorithms are designed to be computed quickly, so if the hashed values are compromised, it is possible to try guessed passwords at high rates.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Common graphics processing units can try billions of possible passwords each second.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Password hash functions that perform key stretching – such as PBKDF2, scrypt or Argon2 – commonly use repeated invocations of a cryptographic hash to increase the time (and in some cases computer memory) required to perform brute-force attacks on stored password hash digests.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For details, see § Attacks on hashed passwords.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A password hash also requires the use of a large random, non-secret salt value that can be stored with the password hash.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The salt is hashed with the password, altering the password hash mapping for each password, thereby making it infeasible for an adversary to store tables of precomputed hash values to which the password hash digest can be compared or to test a large number of purloined hash values in parallel.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A proof-of-work system (or protocol, or function) is an economic measure to deter denial-of-service attacks and other service abuses such as spam on a network by requiring some work from the service requester, usually meaning processing time by a computer.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A key feature of these schemes is their asymmetry: the work must be moderately hard (but feasible) on the requester side but easy to check for the service provider.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] One popular system – used in Bitcoin mining and Hashcash – uses partial hash inversions to prove that work was done, to unlock a mining reward in Bitcoin, and as a good-will token to send an e-mail in Hashcash.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender is required to find a message whose hash value begins with a number of zero bits.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The average work that the sender needs to perform in order to find a valid message is exponential in the number of zero bits required in the hash value, while the recipient can verify the validity of the message by executing a single hash function.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in Hashcash, a sender is asked to generate a header whose 160-bit SHA-1 hash value has the first 20 bits as zeros.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The sender will, on average, have to try 219 times to find a valid header.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A message digest can also serve as a means of reliably identifying a file; several source code management systems, including Git, Mercurial and Monotone, use the sha1sum of various types of content (file content, directory trees, ancestry information, etc.) to uniquely identify them.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Hashes are used to identify files on peer-to-peer filesharing networks.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, in an ed2k link, an MD4-variant hash is combined with the file size, providing sufficient information for locating file sources, downloading the file, and verifying its contents.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Such file hashes are often the top hash of a hash list or a hash tree, which allows for additional benefits.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] One of the main applications of a hash function is to allow the fast look-up of data in a hash table.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Being hash functions of a particular kind, cryptographic hash functions lend themselves well to this application too.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, compared with standard hash functions, cryptographic hash functions tend to be much more expensive computationally.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage (CAS), also referred to as content-addressed storage or fixed-content storage, is a way to store information so it can be retrieved based on its content, not its name or location.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] It has been used for high-speed storage and retrieval of fixed content, such as documents stored for compliance with government regulations.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Content-addressable storage is similar to content-addressable memory.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS systems work by passing the content of the file through a cryptographic hash function to generate a unique key, the "content address".
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The file system's directory stores these addresses and a pointer to the physical storage of the content.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Because an attempt to store the same file will generate the same key, CAS systems ensure that the files within them are unique, and because changing the file will result in a new key, CAS systems provide assurance that the file is unchanged.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] CAS became a significant market during the 2000s, especially after the introduction of the 2002 Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States which required the storage of enormous numbers of documents for long periods and retrieved only rarely.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Ever-increasing performance of traditional file systems and new software systems have eroded the value of legacy CAS systems, which have become increasingly rare after roughly 2018.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, the principles of content addressability continue to be of great interest to computer scientists, and form the core of numerous emerging technologies, such as peer-to-peer file sharing, cryptocurrencies, and distributed computing.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] There are several methods to use a block cipher to build a cryptographic hash function, specifically a one-way compression function.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The methods resemble the block cipher modes of operation usually used for encryption.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Many well-known hash functions, including MD4, MD5, SHA-1 and SHA-2, are built from block-cipher-like components designed for the purpose, with feedback to ensure that the resulting function is not invertible.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 finalists included functions with block-cipher-like components (e.g., Skein, BLAKE) though the function finally selected, Keccak, was built on a cryptographic sponge instead.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A standard block cipher such as AES can be used in place of these custom block ciphers; that might be useful when an embedded system needs to implement both encryption and hashing with minimal code size or hardware area.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] However, that approach can have costs in efficiency and security.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The ciphers in hash functions are built for hashing: they use large keys and blocks, can efficiently change keys every block, and have been designed and vetted for resistance to related-key attacks.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] General-purpose ciphers tend to have different design goals.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In particular, AES has key and block sizes that make it nontrivial to use to generate long hash values; AES encryption becomes less efficient when the key changes each block; and related-key attacks make it potentially less secure for use in a hash function than for encryption.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function must be able to process an arbitrary-length message into a fixed-length output.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This can be achieved by breaking the input up into a series of equally sized blocks, and operating on them in sequence using a one-way compression function.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The compression function can either be specially designed for hashing or be built from a block cipher.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A hash function built with the Merkle–Damgård construction is as resistant to collisions as is its compression function; any collision for the full hash function can be traced back to a collision in the compression function.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The last block processed should also be unambiguously length padded; this is crucial to the security of this construction.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This construction is called the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Most common classical hash functions, including SHA-1 and MD5, take this form.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A straightforward application of the Merkle–Damgård construction, where the size of hash output is equal to the internal state size (between each compression step), results in a **narrow-pipe** hash design.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This design causes many inherent flaws, including length-extension, multicollisions, long message attacks, generate-and-paste attacks, and also cannot be parallelized.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] As a result, modern hash functions are built on **wide-pipe** constructions that have a larger internal state size – which range from tweaks of the Merkle–Damgård construction to new constructions such as the sponge construction and HAIFA construction.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] None of the entrants in the NIST hash function competition use a classical Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Meanwhile, truncating the output of a longer hash, such as used in SHA-512/256, also defeats many of these attacks.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Hash functions can be used to build other cryptographic primitives.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care must be taken to build them correctly.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Message authentication codes (MACs) (also called keyed hash functions) are often built from hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Luby-Rackoff constructions using hash functions can be provably secure if the underlying hash function is secure.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Also, many hash functions (including SHA-1 and SHA-2) are built by using a special-purpose block cipher in a Davies–Meyer or other construction.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] That cipher can also be used in a conventional mode of operation, without the same security guarantees; for example, SHACAL, BEAR and LION.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) can be built using hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This is done by combining a (secret) random seed with a counter and hashing it.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Some hash functions, such as Skein, Keccak, and RadioGatún, output an arbitrarily long stream and can be used as a stream cipher, and stream ciphers can also be built from fixed-length digest hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Often this is done by first building a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator and then using its stream of random bytes as keystream.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is a stream cipher that uses SHA-1 to generate internal tables, which are then used in a keystream generator more or less unrelated to the hash algorithm.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SEAL is not guaranteed to be as strong (or weak) as SHA-1.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Similarly, the key expansion of the HC-128 and HC-256 stream ciphers makes heavy use of the SHA-256 hash function.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Concatenating outputs from multiple hash functions provide collision resistance as good as the strongest of the algorithms included in the concatenated result.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For example, older versions of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) used concatenated MD5 and SHA-1 sums.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This ensures that a method to find collisions in one of the hash functions does not defeat data protected by both hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For Merkle–Damgård construction hash functions, the concatenated function is as collision-resistant as its strongest component, but not more collision-resistant.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Antoine Joux observed that 2-collisions lead to *n*-collisions: if it is feasible for an attacker to find two messages with the same MD5 hash, then they can find as many additional messages with that same MD5 hash as they desire, with no greater difficulty.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Among those *n* messages with the same MD5 hash, there is likely to be a collision in SHA-1.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The additional work needed to find the SHA-1 collision (beyond the exponential birthday search) requires only polynomial time.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] There are many cryptographic hash algorithms; this section lists a few algorithms that are referenced relatively often.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A more extensive list can be found on the page containing a comparison of cryptographic hash functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 was designed by Ronald Rivest in 1991 to replace an earlier hash function, MD4, and was specified in 1992 as RFC 1321.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against MD5 can be calculated within seconds, which makes the algorithm unsuitable for most use cases where a cryptographic hash is required.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] MD5 produces a digest of 128 bits (16 bytes).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The original specification – now commonly called SHA-0 – of the algorithm was published in 1993 under the title Secure Hash Standard, FIPS PUB 180, by U.S. government standards agency NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] It was withdrawn by the NSA shortly after publication and was superseded by the revised version, published in 1995 in FIPS PUB 180-1 and commonly designated SHA-1.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Collisions against the full SHA-1 algorithm can be produced using the shattered attack and the hash function should be considered broken.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-1 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Documents may refer to SHA-1 as just "SHA", even though this may conflict with the other Secure Hash Algorithms such as SHA-0, SHA-2, and SHA-3.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD (RACE Integrity Primitives Evaluation Message Digest) is a family of cryptographic hash functions developed in Leuven, Belgium, by Hans Dobbertin, Antoon Bosselaers, and Bart Preneel at the COSIC research group at the Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, and first published in 1996.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD was based upon the design principles used in MD4 and is similar in performance to the more popular SHA-1.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] RIPEMD-160 has, however, not been broken.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] As the name implies, RIPEMD-160 produces a hash digest of 160 bits (20 bytes).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is a cryptographic hash function designed by Vincent Rijmen and Paulo S.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Barreto, who first described it in 2000.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool is based on a substantially modified version of the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Whirlpool produces a hash digest of 512 bits (64 bytes).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 (Secure Hash Algorithm 2) is a set of cryptographic hash functions designed by the United States National Security Agency (NSA), first published in 2001.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] They are built using the Merkle–Damgård structure, from a one-way compression function itself built using the Davies–Meyer structure from a (classified) specialized block cipher.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-2 basically consists of two hash algorithms: SHA-256 and SHA-512.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-224 is a variant of SHA-256 with different starting values and truncated output.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-512 is more secure than SHA-256 and is commonly faster than SHA-256 on 64-bit machines such as AMD64.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The output size in bits is given by the extension to the "SHA" name, so SHA-224 has an output size of 224 bits (28 bytes); SHA-256, 32 bytes; SHA-384, 48 bytes; and SHA-512, 64 bytes.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 (Secure Hash Algorithm 3) was released by NIST on August 5, 2015.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 is a subset of the broader cryptographic primitive family Keccak.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The Keccak algorithm is the work of Guido Bertoni, Joan Daemen, Michael Peeters, and Gilles Van Assche.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Keccak is based on a sponge construction, which can also be used to build other cryptographic primitives such as a stream cipher.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3 provides the same output sizes as SHA-2: 224, 256, 384, and 512 bits.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Configurable output sizes can also be obtained using the SHAKE-128 and SHAKE-256 functions.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Here the -128 and -256 extensions to the name imply the security strength of the function rather than the output size in bits.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE2, an improved version of BLAKE, was announced on December 21, 2012.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn, and Christian Winnerlein with the goal of replacing the widely used but broken MD5 and SHA-1 algorithms.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] When run on 64-bit x64 and ARM architectures, BLAKE2b is faster than SHA-3, SHA-2, SHA-1, and MD5.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Although BLAKE and BLAKE2 have not been standardized as SHA-3 has, BLAKE2 has been used in many protocols including the Argon2 password hash, for the high efficiency that it offers on modern CPUs.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] As BLAKE was a candidate for SHA-3, BLAKE and BLAKE2 both offer the same output sizes as SHA-3 – including a configurable output size.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3, an improved version of BLAKE2, was announced on January 9, 2020.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] It was created by Jack O'Connor, Jean-Philippe Aumasson, Samuel Neves, and Zooko Wilcox-O'Hearn.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] BLAKE3 is a single algorithm, in contrast to BLAKE and BLAKE2, which are algorithm families with multiple variants.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The BLAKE3 compression function is closely based on that of BLAKE2s, with the biggest difference being that the number of rounds is reduced from 10 to 7.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Internally, BLAKE3 is a Merkle tree, and it supports higher degrees of parallelism than BLAKE2.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] There is a long list of cryptographic hash functions but many have been found to be vulnerable and should not be used.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Even if a hash function has never been broken, a successful attack against a weakened variant may undermine the experts' confidence.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For instance, in August 2004 collisions were found in several then-popular hash functions, including MD5.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] These weaknesses called into question the security of stronger algorithms derived from the weak hash functions – in particular, SHA-1 (a strengthened version of SHA-0), RIPEMD-128, and RIPEMD-160 (both strengthened versions of RIPEMD).
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] On August 12, 2004, Joux, Carribault, Lemuel, and Jalby announced a collision for the full SHA-0 algorithm.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Joux et al. accomplished this using a generalization of the Chabaud and Joux attack.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] They found that the collision had complexity 251 and took about 80,000 CPU hours on a supercomputer with 256 Itanium 2 processors – equivalent to 13 days of full-time use of the supercomputer.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In February 2005, an attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collision in about 269 hashing operations, rather than the 280 expected for a 160-bit hash function.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] In August 2005, another attack on SHA-1 was reported that would find collisions in 263 operations.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Other theoretical weaknesses of SHA-1 have been known, and in February 2017 Google announced a collision in SHA-1.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Security researchers recommend that new applications can avoid these problems by using later members of the SHA family, such as SHA-2, or using techniques such as randomized hashing that do not require collision resistance.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] A successful, practical attack broke MD5 (used within certificates for Transport Layer Security) in 2008.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Many cryptographic hashes are based on the Merkle–Damgård construction.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] All cryptographic hashes that directly use the full output of a Merkle–Damgård construction are vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] This makes the MD5, SHA-1, RIPEMD-160, Whirlpool, and the SHA-256 / SHA-512 hash algorithms all vulnerable to this specific attack.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] SHA-3, BLAKE2, BLAKE3, and the truncated SHA-2 variants are not vulnerable to this type of attack.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Rather than store plain user passwords, controlled-access systems frequently store the hash of each user's password in a file or database.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] When someone requests access, the password they submit is hashed and compared with the stored value.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] If the database is stolen (an all-too-frequent occurrence), the thief will only have the hash values, not the passwords.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Passwords may still be retrieved by an attacker from the hashes, because most people choose passwords in predictable ways.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Lists of common passwords are widely circulated and many passwords are short enough that even all possible combinations may be tested if calculation of the hash does not take too much time.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The use of cryptographic salt prevents some attacks, such as building files of precomputing hash values, e.g. rainbow tables.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] But searches on the order of 100 billion tests per second are possible with high-end graphics processors, making direct attacks possible even with salt.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] The United States National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends storing passwords using special hashes called key derivation functions (KDFs) that have been created to slow brute force searches.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] Slow hashes include pbkdf2, bcrypt, scrypt, argon2, Balloon and some recent modes of Unix crypt.
[src:dm-verity/cryptographic-hash-function] For KDFs that perform multiple hashes to slow execution, NIST recommends an iteration count of 10,000 or more.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] The **device mapper** is a framework provided by the Linux kernel for mapping physical block devices onto higher-level *virtual block devices*.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] It forms the foundation of the logical volume manager (LVM), software RAIDs and dm-crypt disk encryption, and offers additional features such as file system snapshots.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] Device mapper works by passing data from a virtual block device, which is provided by the device mapper itself, to another block device.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] Data can be also modified in transition, which is performed, for example, in the case of device mapper providing disk encryption or simulation of unreliable hardware behavior.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] This article focuses on the device mapper implementation in the Linux kernel, but the device mapper functionality is also available in both NetBSD and DragonFly BSD.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] Applications (like LVM2 and Enterprise Volume Management System (EVMS)) that need to create new mapped devices talk to the device mapper via the `libdevmapper.so` shared library, which in turn issues ioctls to the `/dev/mapper/control` device node.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] Configuration of the device mapper can be also examined and configured interactively‍—‌or from shell scripts‍—‌by using the `dmsetup(8)` utility.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] Both of these two userspace components have their source code maintained alongside the LVM2 source.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] Functions provided by the device mapper include linear, striped and error *mappings,* as well as crypt and multipath *targets.* For example, two disks may be concatenated into one logical volume with a pair of *linear* mappings, one for each disk.
[src:dm-verity/device-mapper] As another example, *crypt* target encrypts the data passing through the specified device, by using the Linux kernel's Crypto API.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The **Linux kernel** is a free and open-source Unix-like kernel that is used in many computer systems worldwide.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 and was soon adopted as the kernel for the GNU operating system (OS), which was created to be a free replacement for Unix.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Since the late 1990s, it has been included in many operating system distributions, many of which are called Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] One such Linux kernel operating system is Android, which is used in many mobile and embedded devices.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the kernel code is written in C as supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), which has extensions beyond standard C.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The code also contains assembly code for architecture-specific logic such as optimizing memory use and task execution.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel has a modular design such that modules can be integrated as software components – including dynamically loaded.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is monolithic in an architectural sense since the entire OS kernel runs in kernel space.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is provided under the GNU General Public License version 2, although it contains files under other compatible licenses.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 1991, Linus Torvalds was a computer science student enrolled at the University of Helsinki.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] During his time there, he began to develop an operating system as a side-project inspired by UNIX, for a personal computer.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] He started with a task switcher in Intel 80386 assembly language and a terminal driver.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] On 17 September 1991, Torvalds prepared version 0.01 of Linux and put on the "ftp.funet.fi" – FTP server of the Finnish University and Research Network (FUNET).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] It was not even executable since its code still needed Minix to compile and test it.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] On 5 October 1991, Torvalds announced the first "official" version of Linux, version 0.02.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] At the time, the GNU Project had completed many components for its free UNIX replacement, GNU, but its kernel, the GNU Hurd, was incomplete.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The project adopted the Linux kernel for its OS.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds labeled the kernel with major version 0 to indicate that it was not yet intended for general use.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.11, released in December 1991, was the first version to be self-hosted; compiled on a computer running the Linux kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] When Torvalds released version 0.12 in January 1992, he adopted the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2) over his previous self-drafted license, which had not permitted commercial redistribution.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In contrast to Unix, all Linux source files are freely available, including device drivers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The initial success of Linux was driven by programmers and testers across the world.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Because Linux implemented Unix-like system call semantics and exposed the standard POSIX APIs through an implementation of the C standard library, Linux could run software and applications that had been originally developed for Unix.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] On 19 January 1992, the first post to the new newsgroup *alt.os.linux* was submitted.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] On 31 March 1992, the newsgroup was renamed *comp.os.linux*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The fact that Linux is a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a debate between Andrew S.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Tanenbaum, the creator of MINIX, and Torvalds.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate started in 1992 on the Usenet group *comp.os.minix* as a general discussion about kernel architectures.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.96 released in May 1992 was the first capable of running the X Window System.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In March 1994, Linux 1.0.0 was released with 176,250 lines of code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As indicated by the version number, it was the first version considered suitable for a production environment.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In June 1996, after release 1.3, Torvalds decided that Linux had evolved enough to warrant a new major number, and so labeled the next release as version 2.0.0.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Significant features of 2.0 included symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), support for more processors types and support for selecting specific hardware targets and for enabling architecture-specific features and optimizations.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The *make *config* family of commands of *kbuild* enable and configure options for building ad hoc kernel executables (vmlinux) and loadable modules.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.2, released on 20 January 1999, improved locking granularity and SMP management, added m68k, PowerPC, Sparc64, Alpha, and other 64-bit platforms support.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, it added new file systems including Microsoft's NTFS read-only capability.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 1999, IBM published its patches to the Linux 2.2.13 code for the support of the S/390 architecture.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.4.0, released on 4 January 2001, contained support for ISA Plug and Play, USB, and PC Cards.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Linux 2.4 added support for the Pentium 4 and Itanium (the latter introduced the ia64 ISA that was jointly developed by Intel and Hewlett-Packard to supersede the older PA-RISC), and for the newer 64-bit MIPS processor.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Development for 2.4.*x* changed a bit in that more features were made available throughout the series, including support for Bluetooth, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) version 1, RAID support, InterMezzo and ext3 file systems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.6.0 was released on 17 December 2003.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The development for 2.6.*x* changed further towards including new features throughout the series.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Starting with 2.6.x releases, the kernel supported a large number of file systems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Some were designed for Linux, like ext3, ext4, FUSE, and Btrfs.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Others were native to other operating systems like JFS, XFS, Minix, Xenix, Irix, Solaris, System V, Windows, and MS-DOS.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Though development had not used a version control system thus far, in 2002, Linux developers adopted BitKeeper, which was made freely available to them even though it was not free software.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005, because of efforts to reverse-engineer it, the company that owned the software revoked its support of the Linux community.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In response, Torvalds and others wrote Git.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The new system was written within weeks, and in two months the first official kernel made using it was released.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005 the *stable team* was formed as a response to the lack of a kernel tree where people could work on bug fixes, and it would keep updating *stable* versions.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In February 2008 the *linux-next* tree was created to serve as a place where patches aimed to be merged during the next development cycle gathered.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Several subsystem maintainers also adopted the suffix *-next* for trees containing code that they mean to submit for inclusion in the next release cycle.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As of January 2014, the in-development version of Linux is held in an unstable branch named *linux-next*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The 20th anniversary of Linux was celebrated by Torvalds in July 2011 with the release of version 3.0.0.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As 2.6 had been the version number for 8 years, a new *uname26* personality that reports 3.x as 2.6.40+x had to be added to the kernel so that old programs would work.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.0 was released on 22 July 2011.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 May 2011, Torvalds announced that the big change was "NOTHING.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Absolutely nothing." and asked, "...let's make sure we really make the next release not just an all new shiny number, but a good kernel too." After the expected 6–7 weeks of the development process, it would be released near the 20th anniversary of Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The same series unified support for the ARM processor.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The numbering change from 2.6.39 to 3.0, and from 3.19 to 4.0, involved no meaningful technical differentiation; the major version number was increased simply to avoid large minor numbers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Stable 3.x.y kernels were released until 3.19 in February 2015.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.11, released on 2 September 2013, added many new features such as the new O_TMPFILE flag for `open(2)` to reduce temporary file vulnerabilities, experimental AMD Radeon dynamic power management, low-latency network polling, and zswap (compressed swap cache).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In April 2015, Torvalds released kernel version 4.0.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] By February 2015, Linux had received contributions from nearly 12,000 programmers from more than 1,200 companies, including some of the world's largest software and hardware vendors.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Version 4.1 of Linux, released in June 2015, contains over 19.5 million lines of code contributed by almost 14,000 programmers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] A total of 1,991 developers, of whom 334 were first-time collaborators, added more than 553,000 lines of code to version 5.8, breaking the record previously held by version 4.9.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] According to the Stack Overflow's annual Developer Survey of 2019, more than 53% of all respondents have developed software for Linux and about 27% for Android, although only about 25% develop with Linux-based operating systems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Most websites run on Linux-based operating systems, and all of the world's 500 most powerful supercomputers run on Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Linux distributions bundle the kernel with system software (e.g., the GNU C Library, systemd, and other Unix utilities and daemons) and a wide selection of application software, but their usage share in desktops is low in comparison to other operating systems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Android, which runs on a modified Linux kernel, accounts for the majority of mobile device operating systems, and is increasingly being used in embedded devices, making it a significant driver of Linux adoption.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The cost to redevelop version 2.6.0 of the Linux kernel in a traditional proprietary development setting has been estimated to be US$612 million (€467M, £394M) in 2004 prices using the COCOMO person-month estimation model.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2006, a study funded by the European Union put the redevelopment cost of kernel version 2.6.8 higher, at €882M ($1.14bn, £744M).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] This topic was revisited in October 2008 by Amanda McPherson, Brian Proffitt, and Ron Hale-Evans.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's methodology, they estimated redevelopment of the 2.6.25 kernel now costs $1.3bn (part of a total $10.8bn to redevelop Fedora 9).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Again, Garcia-Garcia and Alonso de Magdaleno from University of Oviedo (Spain) estimate that the value annually added to kernel was about €100M between 2005 and 2007 and €225M in 2008, it would cost also more than €1bn (about $1.4bn as of February 2010) to develop in the European Union.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As of 7 March 2011, using then-current LOC (lines of code) of a 2.6.x Linux kernel and wage numbers with David A.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's calculations it would cost approximately $3bn (about €2.2bn) to redevelop the Linux kernel as it keeps getting bigger.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] An updated calculation as of 26 September 2018, using then-current 20,088,609 LOC (lines of code) for the 4.14.14 Linux kernel and the current US national average programmer salary of $75,506 show that it would cost approximately $14,725,449,000 (£11,191,341,000) to rewrite the existing code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Most who use Linux do so via a Linux distribution.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Some distributions ship the vanilla or stable kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Several vendors (such as Red Hat and Debian) maintain a customized source tree.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Graph of the sizes of Linux Kernel versions in millions of lines of code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The community of Linux kernel developers comprises about 5000–6000 members.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] According to the "2017 State of Linux Kernel Development", a study issued by the Linux Foundation, covering the commits for the releases 4.8 to 4.13, about 1500 developers were contributing from about 200–250 companies on average.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The top 30 developers contributed a little more than 16% of the code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] For companies, the top contributors are Intel (13.1%) and Red Hat (7.2%), Linaro (5.6%), IBM (4.1%), the second and fifth places are held by the 'none' (8.2%) and 'unknown' (4.1%) categories.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Prominent Linux kernel developers have been aware of the importance of avoiding conflicts between developers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] For a long time there was no code of conduct for kernel developers due to opposition by Torvalds.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] A Linux Kernel *Code of Conflict* was introduced on 8 March 2015.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] It was replaced on 16 September 2018 by a new *Code of Conduct* based on the Contributor Covenant.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] This coincided with a public apology by Torvalds and a brief break from kernel development.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 November 2018, complying with the *Code of Conduct*, Jarkko Sakkinen of Intel sent out patches replacing instances of "fuck" appearing in source code comments with suitable versions focused on the word 'hug'.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Developers who feel treated unfairly can report this to the Linux Foundation Technical Advisory Board.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In July 2013, the maintainer of the USB 3.0 driver Sage Sharp asked Torvalds to address the abusive commentary in the kernel development community.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Sharp backed out of Linux kernel development, saying that "The focus on technical excellence, in combination with overloaded maintainers, and people with different cultural and social norms, means that Linux kernel maintainers are often blunt, rude, or brutal to get their job done".
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] At the linux.conf.au (LCA) conference in 2018, developers expressed the view that the culture of the community has gotten much better in the past few years.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Daniel Vetter, the maintainer of the Intel drm/i915 graphics kernel driver, commented that the "rather violent language and discussion" in the kernel community has decreased or disappeared.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Laurent Pinchart asked developers for feedback on their experiences with the kernel community at the 2017 Embedded Linux Conference Europe.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The issues brought up were discussed a few days later at the Maintainers Summit.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Concerns over the lack of consistency in how maintainers responded to patches submitted by developers were echoed by Shuah Khan, the maintainer of the kernel self-test framework.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds contended that there would never be consistency in the handling of patches because different kernel subsystems have, over time, adopted different development processes.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, it was agreed upon that each kernel subsystem maintainer would document the rules for patch acceptance.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel source code, a.k.a. source tree, is managed in the Git version control system – also created by Torvalds.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As of 2021, the 5.11 release of the Linux kernel had around 30.34 million lines of code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Roughly 14% of the code is part of the "core," including architecture-specific code, kernel code, and memory management code, while 60% is drivers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Contributions are submitted as patches, in the form of text messages on the Linux kernel mailing list (LKML) (and often also on other mailing lists dedicated to particular subsystems).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The patches must conform to a set of rules and to a formal language that, among other things, describes which lines of code are to be deleted and what others are to be added to the specified files.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] These patches can be automatically processed so that system administrators can apply them in order to make just some changes to the code or to incrementally upgrade to the next version.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is distributed also in GNU zip (gzip) and bzip2 formats.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] A developer who wants to change the Linux kernel writes and tests a code change.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Depending on how significant the change is and how many subsystems it modifies, the change will either be submitted as a single patch or in multiple patches of source code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In case of a single subsystem that is maintained by a single maintainer, these patches are sent as e-mails to the maintainer of the subsystem with the appropriate mailing list in Cc.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer and the readers of the mailing list will review the patches and provide feedback.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Once the review process has finished the subsystem maintainer accepts the patches in the relevant Git kernel tree.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] If the changes to the Linux kernel are bug fixes that are considered important enough, a pull request for the patches will be sent to Torvalds within a few days.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Otherwise, a pull request will be sent to Torvalds during the next merge window.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The merge window usually lasts two weeks and starts immediately after the release of the previous kernel version.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The Git kernel source tree names all developers who have contributed to the Linux kernel in the *Credits* directory and all subsystem maintainers are listed in *Maintainers*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As with many large open-source software projects, developers are required to adhere to the Contributor Covenant, a code of conduct intended to address harassment of minority contributors.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Additionally, to prevent offense the use of inclusive terminology within the source code is mandated.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is written in a special C programming language supported by GCC, a compiler that extends the C standard in many ways, for example using inline sections of code written in the assembly language (in GCC's "AT&T-style" syntax) of the target architecture.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Initial support for the Rust programming language was added in Linux 6.1, which was released in December 2022, with later kernel versions, such as Linux 6.2 and Linux 6.3, further improving the support.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As for most software, the kernel is versioned as a series of dot-separated numbers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] For early versions, the version consisted of three or four dot-separated numbers called *major release*, *minor release* and *revision.* At that time, odd-numbered minor releases were for development and testing, while even numbered minor releases for production.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The optional fourth digit indicated a patch level.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Development releases were indicated with a release candidate suffix (*-rc*).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The current versioning conventions are different.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The odd/even number implying dev/prod has been dropped, and a major version is indicated by the first two numbers together.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] While the time-frame is open for the development of the next major, the -rcN suffix is used to identify the n'th release candidate for the next version.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] For example, the release of the version 4.16 was preceded by seven 4.16-rcN (from -rc1 to -rc7).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Once a stable version is released, its maintenance is passed to the *stable team*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Updates to a stable release are identified by a three-number scheme (e.g., 4.16.1, 4.16.2, ...).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is usually built with the GNU toolchain.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU C compiler, GNU cc, part of the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), is the default compiler for mainline Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU Assembler (often called GAS or GNU as) outputs the object files from the GCC generated assembly code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Finally, the GNU Linker (GNU ld) produces a statically linked executable kernel file called vmlinux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Both as and ld are part of GNU Binary Utilities (binutils).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] GNU cc was for a long time the only compiler capable of correctly building Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2004, Intel claimed to have modified the kernel so that its C compiler was also capable of compiling it.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] There was another such reported success in 2009, with a modified 2.6.22 version.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Support for the Intel compiler has been dropped in 2023.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Since 2010, effort has been underway to build Linux with Clang, an alternative compiler for the C language; as of 12 April 2014, the official kernel could almost be compiled by Clang.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The project dedicated to this effort is named *LLVMLinux* after the LLVM compiler infrastructure upon which Clang is built.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] LLVMLinux does not aim to fork either Linux or the LLVM, therefore it is a meta-project composed of patches that are eventually submitted to the upstream projects.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] By enabling Linux to be compiled by Clang, developers may benefit from shorter compilation times.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2017, developers completed upstreaming patches to support building the Linux kernel with Clang in the 4.15 release, having backported support for X86-64 and AArch64 to the 4.4, 4.9, and 4.14 branches of the stable kernel tree.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Google's Pixel 2 shipped with the first Clang built Linux kernel, though patches for Pixel (1st generation) did exist.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] 2018 saw ChromeOS move to building kernels with Clang by default, while Android made Clang and LLVM's linker LLD required for kernel builds in 2019.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Google moved its production kernel used throughout its datacenters to being built with Clang in 2020.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The *ClangBuiltLinux* group coordinates fixes to both Linux and LLVM to ensure compatibility, both composed of members from *LLVMLinux* and having upstreamed patches from *LLVMLinux*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] As with any software, problems with the Linux kernel can be difficult to troubleshoot.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Common challenges relate to userspace vs. kernel space access, misuse of synchronization primitives, and incorrect hardware management.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] An oops is a non-fatal error in the kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, operations continue with suspect reliability.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] A panic (generated by panic()) is a fatal error.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, the kernel prints a message and halts the computer.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel provides for *debugging by printing* via printk(), which stores messages in a circular buffer (overwriting older entries with newer).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The syslog(2) system call provides for reading and clearing the message buffer and for setting the maximum *log level* of the messages to be sent to the console.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Kernel messages are also exported to userland through the */dev/kmsg* interface.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The *ftrace* mechanism allow for debugging by tracing.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] It is used for monitoring and debugging Linux at runtime and it can analyze user space latencies due to kernel misbehavior.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, *ftrace* allows users to trace Linux at boot-time.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] With KGDB Linux can be debugged in much the same way as userspace programs.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] KGDB requires an additional machine that runs GDB and that is connected to the target to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel project integrates new code on a rolling basis.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Standard operating procedure is that software checked into the project must work and compile without error.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Each kernel subsystem is assigned a maintainer who is responsible for reviewing patches against the kernel code standards and keeping a queue of patches that can be submitted to Torvalds within a merge window that is usually several weeks.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Patches are merged by Torvalds into the source code of the prior stable Linux kernel release, creating the release candidate (-rc) for the next stable release.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Once the merge window is closed, only fixes to the new code in the development release are accepted.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The -rc development release of the kernel goes through regression testing and once it is considered stable by Torvalds and the subsystem maintainers, a new version is released and the development process starts over again.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The Git tree that contains the Linux kernel source code is referred to as **mainline Linux**.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Every stable kernel release originates from the mainline tree, and is frequently published on kernel.org.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Mainline Linux has only solid support for a small subset of the many devices that run Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Non-mainline support is provided by independent projects, such as Yocto or Linaro, but in many cases the kernel from the device vendor is needed.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Using a vendor kernel likely requires a board support package.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Maintaining a kernel tree outside of mainline Linux has proven to be difficult.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer of the stable branch, Greg Kroah-Hartman, has applied the term *Linux-like* to downstream kernel forks by vendors that add millions of lines of code to the mainline kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2019, Google stated that it wanted to use the mainline Linux kernel in Android so the number of kernel forks would be reduced.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The term Linux-like has also been applied to the Embeddable Linux Kernel Subset, which does not include the full mainline Linux kernel but a small modified subset of the code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] There are certain communities that develop kernels based on the official Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Some interesting bits of code from these forks that include Linux-libre, Compute Node Linux, INK, L4Linux, RTLinux, and User-Mode Linux (UML) have been merged into the mainline.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Some operating systems developed for mobile phones initially used heavily modified versions of Linux, including Google Android, Firefox OS, HP webOS, Nokia Maemo and Jolla Sailfish OS.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Today Android uses a customized Linux where major changes are implemented in device drivers, but some changes to the core kernel code is required.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Android developers also submit patches to the official Linux that finally can boot the Android operating system.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] For example, a Nexus 7 can boot and run the mainline Linux.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The latest version and older versions are maintained separately.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the latest kernel releases were supervised by Torvalds.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel developer community maintains a stable kernel by applying fixes for software bugs that have been discovered during the development of the subsequent stable kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, www.kernel.org always lists two stable kernels.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] The next stable Linux kernel is released about 8 to 12 weeks later.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Some releases are designated for long-term support as *longterm* with bug fix releases for two or more years.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] Some projects have attempted to reduce the size of the Linux kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Josh Triplett started the -tiny source tree for a reduced size version.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Even though seemingly contradictory, the Linux kernel is both monolithic and modular.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is classified as a monolithic kernel architecturally since the entire OS runs in kernel space.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The design is modular since it can be assembled from modules that in some cases are loaded and unloaded at runtime.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] It supports features once only available in closed source kernels of non-free operating systems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The rest of the article makes use of the UNIX and Unix-like operating systems convention of the manual pages.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The number that follows the name of a command, interface, or other feature specifies the section (i.e. the type of the OS' component or feature) it belongs to.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] For example execve(2) refers to a system call, and exec(3) refers to a userspace library wrapper.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The following is an overview of architectural design and of noteworthy features.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Most device drivers and kernel extensions run in kernel space (ring 0 in many CPU architectures), with full access to the hardware.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Some exceptions run in user space; notable examples are filesystems based on FUSE/CUSE, and parts of UIO.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Furthermore, the X Window System and Wayland, the windowing system and display server protocols that most people use with Linux, do not run within the kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Differently, the actual interfacing with GPUs of graphics cards is an in-kernel subsystem called Direct Rendering Manager (DRM).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike standard monolithic kernels, device drivers are easily configured as modules, and loaded or unloaded while the system is running and can also be pre-empted under certain conditions in order to handle hardware interrupts correctly and to better support symmetric multiprocessing.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] By choice, Linux has no stable device driver application binary interface.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux typically makes use of memory protection and virtual memory and can also handle non-uniform memory access, the project has absorbed μClinux, which also makes it possible to run Linux on microcontrollers without virtual memory.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The hardware is represented in the file hierarchy.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] User applications interact with device drivers via entries in the /dev or /sys directories.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Process information is mapped into the /proc directory.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux started as a clone of UNIX, and aims toward POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides system calls and other interfaces that are Linux-specific.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In order to be included in the official kernel, the code must comply with a set of licensing rules.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux application binary interface (ABI) between the kernel and the user space has four degrees of stability (stable, testing, obsolete, removed); The system calls are expected to never change in order to preserve compatibility for userspace programs that rely on them.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Loadable kernel modules (LKMs), by design, cannot rely on a stable ABI.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Therefore, they must always be recompiled whenever a new kernel executable is installed in a system, otherwise they will not be loaded.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In-tree drivers that are configured to become an integral part of the kernel executable (vmlinux) are statically linked by the build process.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] There is no guarantee of stability of source-level in-kernel API and, because of this, device driver code, as well as the code of any other kernel subsystem, must be kept updated with kernel evolution.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Any developer who makes an API change is required to fix any code that breaks as the result of their change.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The set of the Linux kernel API that regards the interfaces exposed to user applications is fundamentally composed of UNIX and Linux-specific system calls.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] A system call is an entry point into the Linux kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] For example, among the Linux-specific ones there is the family of the clone(2) system calls.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Most extensions must be enabled by defining the `_GNU_SOURCE` macro in a header file or when the user-land code is being compiled.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] System calls can only be invoked via assembly instructions that enable the transition from unprivileged user space to privileged kernel space in ring 0.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] For this reason, the C standard library (libC) acts as a wrapper to most Linux system calls, by exposing C functions that, if needed, transparently enter the kernel, which will execute on behalf of the calling process.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] For system calls not exposed by libC, such as the fast userspace mutex, the library provides a function called syscall(2), which can be used to explicitly invoke them.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Pseudo filesystems (e.g., the sysfs and procfs filesystems) and special files (e.g., `/dev/random`, `/dev/sda`, `/dev/tty`, and many others) constitute another layer of interface to kernel data structures representing hardware or logical (software) devices.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This issue is mainly due to distribution-specific configurations and a set of patches applied to the code of the Linux kernel, differences in system libraries, services (daemons), filesystem hierarchies, and environment variables.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The main standard concerning application and binary compatibility of Linux distributions is the Linux Standard Base (LSB).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB goes beyond what concerns the Linux kernel, because it also defines the desktop specifications, the X libraries and Qt that have little to do with it.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB version 5 is built upon several standards and drafts (POSIX, SUS, X/Open, File System Hierarchy (FHS), and others).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The standard ABI for how x86_64 user programs invoke system calls is to load the syscall number into the *rax* register, and the other parameters into *rdi*, *rsi*, *rdx*, *r10*, *r8*, and *r9*, and finally to put the *syscall* assembly instruction in the code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] There are several internal kernel APIs between kernel subsystems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux developers chose not to maintain a stable in-kernel ABI.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Modules compiled for a specific version of the kernel cannot be loaded into another version without being recompiled.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux, as other kernels, has the ability to manage processes including creating, suspending, resuming and terminating.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike other operating systems, the Linux kernel implements processes as a group of threads called tasks.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] If two tasks share the same TGID, then they are called in the kernel terminology a task group.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Each task is represented by a *task_struct* data structure.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] A new process can be created by calling clone family of system calls or fork system call.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Processes can be suspended and resumed by the kernel by sending signals like SIGSTOP and SIGCONT.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] A process can terminate itself by calling exit system call, or terminated by another process by sending signals like SIGKILL, SIGABRT or SIGINT.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] If the executable is dynamically linked to shared libraries, a dynamic linker is used to find and load the needed objects, prepare the program to run and then run it.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The Native POSIX Thread Library (NPTL) provides the POSIX standard thread interface (*pthreads*) to userspace.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel isn't aware of processes nor threads but it is aware of *tasks*, thus threads are implemented in userspace.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Threads in Linux are implemented as *tasks* sharing resources, while if they aren't sharing called to be independent processes.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides the futex(7) (fast user-space mutex) mechanisms for user-space locking and synchronization.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The majority of the operations are performed in userspace but it may be necessary to communicate with the kernel using the futex(2) system call.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] As opposed to userspace threads described above, *kernel threads* run in kernel space.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] They are threads created by the kernel itself for specialized tasks; they are privileged like the kernel and aren't bound to any process or application.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux process scheduler is modular, in the sense that it enables different scheduling classes and policies.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Scheduler classes are pluggable scheduler algorithms that can be registered with the base scheduler code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Each class schedules different types of processes.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The core code of the scheduler iterates over each class in order of priority and chooses the highest priority scheduler that has a schedulable entity of type struct sched_entity ready to run.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Entities may be threads, group of threads, and even all the processes of a specific user.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux provides both user preemption as well as (selectable, up to) full kernel preemption.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Preemption reduces latency, increases responsiveness, and makes Linux more suitable for desktop and real-time applications.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This comes at a cost of throughput, as work being interrupted worsens cache behavior.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] For normal tasks, by default, the kernel uses the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) class, introduced in version 2.6.23.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The scheduler is defined as a macro in a C header as `SCHED_NORMAL`.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In other POSIX kernels, a similar policy known as `SCHED_OTHER` allocates CPU timeslices (i.e, it assigns absolute slices of the processor time depending on either predetermined or dynamically computed priority of each process).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] With user preemption, the kernel scheduler can replace the current process with the execution of a context switch to a different one that therefore acquires the computing resources for running (CPU, memory, and more).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] With kernel preemption, the kernel can preempt itself when an interrupt handler returns, when kernel tasks block, and whenever a subsystem explicitly calls the schedule() function.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel also contains two POSIX-compliant real-time scheduling classes named `SCHED_FIFO` (realtime first-in-first-out) and `SCHED_RR` (realtime round-robin), both of which take precedence over the default class.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] An additional scheduling policy known as `SCHED_DEADLINE`, implementing the earliest deadline first algorithm (EDF), was added in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] `SCHED_DEADLINE` takes precedence over all the other scheduling classes.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) scheduler, to prevent the need for CFS "latency nice" patches.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The EEVDF scheduler replaced CFS in version 6.6 of the Linux kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel has different causes of concurrency (e.g., interrupts, bottom halves, preemption of kernel and users tasks, symmetrical multiprocessing).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] They consist of atomic types (which can only be manipulated by a set of specific operators), spinlocks, semaphores, mutexes, and lockless algorithms (e.g., RCUs).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Most lock-less algorithms are built on top of memory barriers for the purpose of enforcing memory ordering and prevent undesired side effects due to compiler optimization.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] PREEMPT_RT code included in mainline Linux provide *RT-mutexes*, a special kind of Mutex that do not disable preemption and have support for priority inheritance.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Almost all locks are changed into sleeping locks when using configuration for realtime operation.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Priority inheritance avoids priority inversion by granting a low-priority task that holds a contended lock the priority of a higher-priority waiter until that lock is released.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux includes a kernel lock validator called *Lockdep*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Although the management of interrupts could be seen as a single job, it is divided into two.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This split in two is due to the different time constraints and to the synchronization needs of the tasks whose the management is composed of.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The first part is made up of an asynchronous interrupt service routine (ISR) that in Linux is known as the *top half*, while the second part is carried out by one of three types of the so-called *bottom halves* (*softirq*, *tasklets,* and *work queues*).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux interrupt service routines can be nested.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] A new IRQ can trap into a high priority ISR that preempts any other lower priority ISR.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel manages both physical and virtual memory.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] It divides physical memory into zones, each of which has a specific purpose.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Those zones are the most common, but others exist.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux implements virtual memory with 4 or 5-level page tables.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is not pageable (meaning it is always resident in physical memory and cannot be swapped to the disk) and there is no memory protection (no SIGSEGV signals, unlike in user space), therefore memory violations lead to instability and system crashes.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] User memory is pageable by default, although paging for specific memory areas can be disabled with the `mlock()` system call family.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Page frame information is maintained in apposite data structures (of type `struct page`) that are populated immediately after boot and kept until shutdown, regardless of whether they are associated with virtual pages.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The physical address space is divided into different zones, according to architectural constraints and intended use.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] NUMA systems with multiple memory banks are also supported.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Small chunks of memory can be dynamically allocated in kernel space via the family of `kmalloc()` APIs and freed with the appropriate variant of `kfree()`.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] `vmalloc()` and `kvfree()` are used for large virtually contiguous chunks.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] `alloc_pages()` allocates the desired number of entire pages.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel used to include the SLAB, SLUB and SLOB allocators as configurable alternatives.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The SLOB allocator was removed in Linux 6.4 and the SLAB allocator was removed in Linux 6.8.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The sole remaining allocator is SLUB, which aims for simplicity and efficiency, is PREEMPT_RT compatible and was introduced in Linux 2.6.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Since Linux supports numerous filesystems with different features and functionality, it is necessary to implement a generic filesystem that is independent from underlying filesystems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The virtual file system interfaces with other Linux subsystems, userspace, or APIs and abstracts away the different implementations of underlying filesystems.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements system calls like `create`, `open`, `read`, `write` and `close`.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements a generic superblock and inode block that is independent from the one that the underlying filesystem has.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In this subsystem directories and files are represented by a `struct file` data structure.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] When userspace requests access to a file it is returned a file descriptor (non negative integer value) but in kernel space it is a `struct file` structure.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This structure stores all the information the kernel knows about a file or directory.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] sysfs and procfs are virtual filesystems that expose hardware information and userspace programs' runtime information.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] These filesystems aren't present on disk and instead the kernel implements them as a callback or routine that gets called when they are accessed by userspace.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] While not originally designed to be portable, Linux is now one of the most widely ported operating system kernels, running on a diverse range of systems from the ARM architecture to IBM z/Architecture mainframe computers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The first port was performed on the Motorola 68000 platform.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The modifications to the kernel were so fundamental that Torvalds viewed the Motorola version as a fork and a "Linux-like operating system".
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] That moved Torvalds to lead a major restructure of the code to facilitate porting to more computing architectures.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The first Linux that, in a single source tree, had code for more than i386 alone, supported the DEC Alpha AXP 64-bit platform.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is used as the primary operating system on IBM’s Summit supercomputer.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2019, all systems on the TOP500 list of the world’s fastest supercomputers ran operating systems based on the Linux kernel, whereas the first Linux-based supercomputer appeared on the list in 1998.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux has also been ported to various handheld devices such as iPhone 3G and iPod.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In 2007, the LKDDb project has been started to build a comprehensive database of hardware and protocols known by Linux kernels.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The database is built automatically by static analysis of the kernel sources.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Later in 2014, the Linux Hardware project was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations with the help of users of various Linux distributions.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel updates can be applied without rebooting by using live patching technologies such as Ksplice, kpatch and kGraft.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Initial support for live kernel patching was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 4.0, released on 12 April 2015.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The feature, known as *livepatch*, uses the kernel's ftrace functionality and provides a common infrastructure for hot patches supplied through kernel modules, together with interfaces for userspace management tools.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In its initial Linux 4.0 implementation, livepatch support was limited to the x86 architecture and provided basic infrastructure rather than a complete live-patching consistency model.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel bugs present potential security issues.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] For example, they may allow for privilege escalation or create denial-of-service attack vectors.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Over the years, numerous bugs affecting system security were found and fixed.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] New features are frequently implemented to improve the kernel's security.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Capabilities(7) have already been introduced in the section about the processes and threads.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Android makes use of them and systemd gives administrators detailed control over the capabilities of processes.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux offers a wealth of mechanisms to reduce kernel attack surface and improve security that are collectively known as the Linux Security Modules (LSM).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] They comprise the Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) module, whose code has been originally developed and then released to the public by the NSA, and AppArmor among others.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux is now actively developed and maintained on GitHub.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux and AppArmor provide support to access control security policies, including mandatory access control (MAC), though they profoundly differ in complexity and scope.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Another security feature is the Seccomp BPF (SECure COMPuting with Berkeley Packet Filters), which works by filtering parameters and reducing the set of system calls available to user-land applications.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux distributions typically release security updates to fix vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Many offer long-term support releases that receive security updates for a certain Linux kernel version for an extended period of time.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In 2024, researchers disclosed that the Linux kernel contained a serious vulnerability, CVE-2024-50264, located in the AF_VSOCK subsystem.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This bug is a use-after-free flaw, a class of memory corruption issue that occurs when a program continues to use memory after it has been freed.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Such flaws are particularly dangerous in the kernel, as they can allow attackers to escalate privileges.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Initially, Torvalds released Linux under a license that forbade any commercial use.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This was changed in version 0.12 by a switch to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] This license allows distribution and sale of possibly modified and unmodified versions of Linux but requires that all those copies be released under the same license and be accompanied by - or that, on request, free access is given to - the complete corresponding source code.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds has described licensing Linux under the GPLv2 as the "best thing I ever did".
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel is licensed explicitly under GNU General Public License version 2 only (GPL-2.0-only) with an explicit syscall exception (Linux-syscall-note), without offering the licensee the option to choose any later version, which is a common GPL extension.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Contributed code must be available under GPL-compatible license.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] There was considerable debate about how easily the license could be changed to use later GPL versions (including version 3), and whether this change is even desirable.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds himself specifically indicated upon the release of version 2.4.0 that his own code is released only under version 2.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The terms of the GPL state that if no version is specified, then any version may be used, and Alan Cox pointed out that very few other Linux contributors had specified a particular version of the GPL.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In September 2006, a survey of 29 key kernel programmers indicated that 28 preferred GPLv2 to the then-current GPLv3 draft.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] They referred to clauses regarding DRM/tivoization, patents, "additional restrictions" and warned a Balkanisation of the "Open Source Universe" by the GPLv3.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds, who decided not to adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel, reiterated his criticism even years later.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] It is debated whether some loadable kernel modules (LKMs) are to be considered derivative works under copyright law, and thereby whether or not they fall under the terms of the GPL.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In accordance with the license rules, LKMs using only a public subset of the kernel interfaces are non-derived works, thus Linux gives system administrators the mechanisms to load out-of-tree binary objects into the kernel address space.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] There are some out-of-tree loadable modules that make legitimate use of the *dma_buf* kernel feature.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] GPL compliant code can certainly use it.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] A different possible use case would be Nvidia Optimus that pairs a fast GPU with an Intel integrated GPU, where the Nvidia GPU writes into the Intel framebuffer when it is active.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] But, Nvidia cannot use this infrastructure because it necessitates bypassing a rule that can only be used by LKMs that are also GPL.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Alan Cox replied on LKML, rejecting a request from one of Nvidia's engineers to remove this technical enforcement from the API.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds clearly stated on the LKML that "[I] claim that binary-only kernel modules ARE derivative "by default"'".
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] On the other hand, Torvalds has also said that "[one] gray area in particular is something like a driver that was originally written for another operating system (i.e., clearly not a derived work of Linux in origin).
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] THAT is a gray area, and _that_ is the area where I personally believe that some modules may be considered to not be derived works simply because they weren't designed for Linux and don't depend on any special Linux behaviour".
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Proprietary graphics drivers, in particular, are heavily discussed.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Whenever proprietary modules are loaded into Linux, the kernel marks itself as being "tainted", and therefore bug reports from tainted kernels will often be ignored by developers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] The official kernel, that is, Torvalds's git branch at the kernel.org repository, contains binary blobs released under the terms of the GNU GPLv2 license.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux can also load binary blobs, proprietary firmware, drivers, or other executable modules from the filesystem, and link them into kernel space.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is a registered trademark of Linus Torvalds in the United States, the European Union, and some other countries.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] A legal battle over the trademark began in 1996, when William Della Croce, a lawyer who was never involved in the development of Linux, started requesting licensing fees for the use of the word *Linux*.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] After it was proven that the word was in common use long before Della Croce's claimed first use, the trademark was awarded to Torvalds.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2024, during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, kernel developer Greg Kroah-Hartman removed some kernel developers whose email addresses suggested a connection to Russia from their roles as maintainers.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] Linus Torvalds responded that he did not support Russian aggression and would not revert the patch, insinuating that opponents of the patch were Russian trolls.
[src:dm-verity/linux-kernel-p02] James Bottomley, a kernel developer, issued an apology for the handling of the situation and clarified that the action was a consequence of U.S. sanctions against Russia.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] A hash tree allows efficient and secure verification of the contents of a large data structure.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a generalization of a hash list and a hash chain.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Demonstrating that a leaf node is a part of a given binary hash tree requires computing a number of hashes proportional to the logarithm of the number of leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Conversely, in a hash list, the number is proportional to the number of leaf nodes itself.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] A Merkle tree is therefore an efficient example of a cryptographic commitment scheme, in which the root of the tree is seen as a commitment and leaf nodes may be revealed and proven to be part of the original commitment.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] The concept of a hash tree is named after Ralph Merkle, who patented it in 1979.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Hash trees can be used to verify any kind of data stored, handled and transferred in and between computers.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] They can help ensure that data blocks received from other peers in a peer-to-peer network are received undamaged and unaltered, and even to check that the other peers do not lie and send fake blocks.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Suggestions have been made to use hash trees in trusted computing systems.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a tree of hashes in which the leaves (i.e., leaf nodes, sometimes also called "leafs") are hashes of data blocks in, for instance, a file or set of files.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Nodes farther up in the tree are the hashes of their respective children.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] For example, in the above picture *hash 0* is the result of hashing the concatenation of *hash 0-0* and *hash 0-1*.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] That is, *hash 0* = *hash*( *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1* ) where "+" denotes concatenation.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Most hash tree implementations are binary (two child nodes under each node) but they can just as well use many more child nodes under each node.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Usually, a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-2 is used for the hashing.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] If the hash tree only needs to protect against unintentional damage, non-cryptographic checksums such as CRCs can be used.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] In the top of a hash tree there is a *top hash* (or *root hash* or *master hash*).
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Before downloading a file on a P2P network, in most cases the top hash is acquired from a trusted source, for instance a friend or a web site that is known to have good recommendations of files to download.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] When the top hash is available, the hash tree can be received from any non-trusted source, like any peer in the P2P network.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Then, the received hash tree is checked against the trusted top hash, and if the hash tree is damaged or fake, another hash tree from another source will be tried until the program finds one that matches the top hash.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] The main difference from a hash list is that one branch of the hash tree can be downloaded at a time and the integrity of each branch can be checked immediately, even though the whole tree is not available yet.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] For example, in the picture, the integrity of *data block L2* can be verified immediately if the tree already contains *hash 0-0* and *hash 1* by hashing the data block and iteratively combining the result with *hash 0-0* and then *hash 1* and finally comparing the result with the *top hash*.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Similarly, the integrity of *data block L3* can be verified if the tree already has *hash 1-1* and *hash 0*.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] This can be an advantage since it is efficient to split files up in very small data blocks so that only small blocks have to be re-downloaded if they get damaged.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] If the hashed file is big, such a hash list or hash chain becomes fairly big.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] But if it is a tree, one small branch can be downloaded quickly, the integrity of the branch can be checked, and then the downloading of data blocks can start.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] The Merkle hash root does not indicate the tree depth, enabling a second-preimage attack in which an attacker creates a document other than the original that has the same Merkle hash root.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] For the example above, an attacker can create a new document containing two data blocks, where the first is *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1*, and the second is *hash 1-0* + *hash 1-1*.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] One simple fix is defined in Certificate Transparency: when computing leaf node hashes, a 0x00 byte is prepended to the hash data, while 0x01 is prepended when computing internal node hashes.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Limiting the hash tree size is a prerequisite of some formal security proofs, and helps in making some proofs tighter.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Some implementations limit the tree depth using hash tree depth prefixes before hashes, so any extracted hash chain is defined to be valid only if the prefix decreases at each step and is still positive when the leaf is reached.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] The Tiger tree hash is a widely used form of hash tree.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] It uses a binary hash tree (two child nodes under each node), usually has a data block size of 1024 bytes and uses the Tiger hash.
[src:dm-verity/merkle-tree] Tiger tree hashes are used in Gnutella, Gnutella2, and Direct Connect P2P file sharing protocols and in file sharing applications such as Phex, BearShare, LimeWire, Shareaza, DC++ and gtk-gnutella.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Strictly speaking, *read-only memory* refers to hard-wired memory, such as diode matrix or a mask ROM integrated circuit (IC), that cannot be electronically changed after manufacture.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Although discrete circuits can be altered in principle, through the addition of bodge wires and the removal or replacement of components, ICs cannot.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Correction of errors, or updates to the software, require new devices to be manufactured and to replace the installed device.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Floating-gate ROM semiconductor memory in the form of erasable programmable read-only memory (EPROM), electrically erasable programmable read-only memory (EEPROM) and flash memory can be erased and re-programmed.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] But usually, this can only be done at relatively slow speeds, may require special equipment to achieve, and is typically only possible a certain number of times.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The term "ROM" is sometimes used to refer to a ROM device containing specific software or a file with software to be stored in a writable ROM device.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] ROM and RAM are essential components of a computer, each serving distinct roles.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] RAM, or random access memory, is a temporary, volatile storage medium that loses data when the system powers down.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In contrast, ROM, being non-volatile, preserves its data even after the computer is switched off.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] IBM used capacitor read-only storage (CROS) and transformer read-only storage (TROS) to store microcode for the smaller System/360 models, the 360/85, and the initial two System/370 models (370/155 and 370/165).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] On some models there was also a writeable control store (WCS) for additional diagnostics and emulation support.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The Apollo Guidance Computer used core rope memory, programmed by threading wires through magnetic cores.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The simplest type of solid-state ROM is as old as the semiconductor technology itself.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Combinational logic gates can be joined manually to map n-bit address input onto arbitrary values of m-bit data output (a look-up table).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] With the invention of the integrated circuit came mask ROM.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Mask ROM consists of a grid of word lines (the address input) and bit lines (the data output), selectively joined with transistor switches, and can represent an arbitrary look-up table with a regular physical layout and predictable propagation delay.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Mask ROM is programmed with photomasks in photolithography during semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The mask defines physical features or structures that will be removed, or added in the ROM chips, and the presence or absence of these features will represent either a 1 or a 0 bit, depending on the ROM design.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Thus by design, any attempts to electronically change the data will fail, since the data is defined by the presence or absence of physical features or structures that cannot be electronically changed.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] For every software program, even for revisions of the same program, the entire mask must be changed, which can be costly.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In mask ROM, the data is physically encoded in the circuit, so it can only be programmed during fabrication.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Subsequent developments have addressed these shortcomings.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Programmable read-only memory (PROM), invented by Wen Tsing Chow in 1956, allowed users to program its contents exactly once by physically altering its structure with the application of high-voltage pulses.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This addressed problems 1 and 2 above, since a company can simply order a large batch of fresh PROM chips and program them with the desired contents at its designers' convenience.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In 1967, Dawon Kahng and Simon Sze of Bell Labs proposed that the floating gate of a MOS semiconductor device could be used for the cell of a reprogrammable ROM, which led to Dov Frohman of Intel inventing erasable programmable read-only memory (EPROM) in 1971.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The 1971 invention of EPROM essentially solved problem 3, since EPROM (unlike PROM) can be repeatedly reset to its unprogrammed state by exposure to strong ultraviolet light.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Flash memory, invented by Fujio Masuoka at Toshiba in the early 1980s and commercialized in the late 1980s, is a form of EEPROM that makes very efficient use of chip area and can be erased and reprogrammed thousands of times without damage.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] It permits erasure and programming of only a specific part of the device, instead of the entire device.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This can be done at high speed, hence the name "flash".
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] All of these technologies improved the flexibility of ROM, but at a significant cost-per-chip, so that in large quantities mask ROM would remain an economical choice for many years.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] (Decreasing cost of reprogrammable devices had almost eliminated the market for mask ROM by the year 2000.) Rewriteable technologies were envisioned as replacements for mask ROM.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The most recent development is NAND flash, also invented at Toshiba.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Its designers explicitly broke from past practice, stating plainly that "the aim of NAND flash is to replace hard disks," rather than the traditional use of ROM as a form of non-volatile primary storage.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] As of 2021, NAND has nearly completely achieved this goal by offering throughput higher than hard disks, lower latency, higher tolerance of physical shock, extreme miniaturization (in the form of USB flash drives and tiny microSD memory cards, for example), and much lower power consumption.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Likewise, every non-trivial computer needs some form of mutable memory to record changes in its state as it executes.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Forms of read-only memory were employed as non-volatile storage for programs in most early stored-program computers, such as ENIAC after 1948.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Consequently, ROM could be implemented at a lower cost-per-bit than RAM for many years.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Most home computers of the 1980s stored a BASIC interpreter or operating system in ROM as other forms of non-volatile storage such as magnetic disk drives were too costly.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] For example, the Commodore 64 included 64 KB of RAM and 20 KB of ROM containing a BASIC interpreter and the KERNAL operating system.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This arrangement allowed for a more complex and easily upgradeable operating system.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In modern PCs, "ROM" is used to store the basic bootstrapping firmware for the processor, as well as the various firmware needed to internally control self-contained devices such as graphic cards, hard disk drives, solid-state drives, optical disc drives, TFT screens, etc., in the system.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Today, many of these "read-only" memories – especially the BIOS/UEFI – are often replaced with EEPROM or Flash memory (see below), to permit in-place reprogramming should the need for a firmware upgrade arise.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] However, simple and mature sub-systems (such as the keyboard or some communication controllers in the integrated circuits on the main board, for example) may employ mask ROM or OTP (one-time programmable).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] ROM and successor technologies such as flash are prevalent in embedded systems.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] These are in everything from industrial robots to home appliances and consumer electronics (MP3 players, set-top boxes, etc.) all of which are designed for specific functions, but are based on general-purpose microprocessors.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] With software usually tightly coupled to hardware, program changes are rarely needed in such devices (which typically lack hard disks for reasons of cost, size, or power consumption).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] As of 2008, most products use Flash rather than mask ROM, and many provide some means for connecting to a PC for firmware updates; for example, a digital audio player might be updated to support a new file format.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Some hobbyists have taken advantage of this flexibility to reprogram consumer products for new purposes; for example, the iPodLinux and OpenWrt projects have enabled users to run full-featured Linux distributions on their MP3 players and wireless routers, respectively.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] ROM is also useful for binary storage of cryptographic data, as it makes them difficult to replace, which may be desirable in order to enhance information security.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Since ROM (at least in hard-wired mask form) cannot be modified, it is only suitable for storing data which is not expected to need modification for the life of the device.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] To that end, ROM has been used in many computers to store look-up tables for the evaluation of mathematical and logical functions (for example, a floating-point unit might tabulate the sine function in order to facilitate faster computation).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This was especially effective when CPUs were slow and ROM was cheap compared to RAM.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Notably, the display adapters of early personal computers stored tables of bitmapped font characters in ROM.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This usually meant that the text display font could not be changed interactively.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This was the case for both the CGA and MDA adapters available with the IBM PC (type 5150).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The use of ROM to store such small amounts of data has disappeared almost completely in modern general-purpose computers.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] However, NAND Flash has taken over a new role as a medium for mass storage or secondary storage of files.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Mask ROM transistors can be arranged in either NOR or NAND configurations and can achieve one of the smallest cell sizes possible as each bit is represented by only one transistor.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] NAND offers higher storage density than NOR.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] OR configurations are also possible, but compared to NOR it only connects transistors to Vcc instead of Vss.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Mask ROMs used to be the most inexpensive, and are the simplest semiconductor memory devices, with only one metal layer and one polysilicon layer, making it the type of semiconductor memory with the highest manufacturing yield (the highest number of working devices per manufacturing run).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] ROM can be made using one of several semiconductor device fabrication technologies such as CMOS, nMOS, pMOS, and bipolar transistors.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] It is common practice to use rewritable non-volatile memory – such as UV-EPROM or EEPROM – for the development phase of a project, and to switch to mask ROM when the code has been finalized.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] For example, Atmel microcontrollers come in both EEPROM and mask ROM formats.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The main advantage of mask ROM is its cost.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Per bit, mask ROM was more compact than any other kind of semiconductor memory.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Since the cost of an integrated circuit strongly depends on its size, mask ROM is significantly cheaper than any other kind of semiconductor memory.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] However, the one-time masking cost is high and there is a long turn-around time from design to product phase.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Design errors are costly: if an error in the data or code is found, the mask ROM is useless and must be replaced in order to change the code or data.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] As of 2003, four companies produce most such mask ROM chips: Samsung Electronics, NEC Corporation, Oki Electric Industry, and Macronix.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Some integrated circuits contain only mask ROM.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Other integrated circuits contain mask ROM as well as a variety of other devices.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In particular, many microprocessors have mask ROM to store their microcode.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Some microcontrollers have mask ROM to store the bootloader or all of their firmware.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Classic mask-programmed ROM chips are integrated circuits that physically encode the data to be stored, and thus it is impossible to change their contents after fabrication.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] It is also possible to write the contents of a Laser ROM by using a laser to alter the electrical properties of only some diodes on the ROM, or by using a laser to cut only some polysilicon links, instead of using a mask.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] By applying write protection, some types of reprogrammable ROMs may temporarily become read-only memory.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] ROM has varied over time, as of 2007 large RAM chips can be read faster than most ROMs.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] For this reason (and to allow uniform access), ROM content is sometimes copied to RAM or **shadowed** before its first use, and subsequently read from RAM.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] For those types of ROM that can be electrically modified, writing speed has traditionally been much slower than reading speed, and it may need unusually high voltage, the movement of jumper plugs to apply write-enable signals, and special lock/unlock command codes.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Modern NAND Flash can be used to achieve the highest write speeds of any rewritable ROM technology, with speeds as high as 10 GB/s in an SSD.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This has been enabled by the increased investment in both consumer and enterprise solid-state drives and flash memory products for higher end mobile devices.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] On a technical level the gains have been achieved by increasing parallelism both in controller design and of storage, the use of large DRAM read/write caches and the implementation of memory cells which can store more than one bit (DLC, TLC and MLC).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The latter approach is more failure prone but this has been largely mitigated by overprovisioning (the inclusion of spare capacity in a product which is visible only to the drive controller) and by increasingly sophisticated read/write algorithms in drive firmware.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Because they are written by forcing electrons through a layer of electrical insulation onto a floating transistor gate, rewriteable ROMs can withstand only a limited number of write and erase cycles before the insulation is permanently damaged.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In the earliest EPROMs, this might occur after as few as 1,000 write cycles, while in modern Flash EEPROM the endurance may exceed 1,000,000.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The limited endurance, as well as the higher cost per bit, means that Flash-based storage is unlikely to completely supplant magnetic disk drives in the near future.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The timespan over which a ROM remains accurately readable is not limited by write cycling.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The data retention of EPROM, EAROM, EEPROM, and Flash may be time-limited by charge leaking from the floating gates of the memory cell transistors.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Early generation EEPROM's, in the mid-1980s generally cited 5 or 6 year data retention.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] A review of EEPROM's offered in the year 2020 shows manufacturers citing 100 year data retention.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Adverse environments will reduce the retention time (leakage is accelerated by high temperatures or radiation).
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Masked ROM and fuse/antifuse PROM do not suffer from this effect, as their data retention depends on physical rather than electrical permanence of the integrated circuit, although fuse re-growth was once a problem in some systems.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The contents of ROM chips can be extracted with special hardware devices and relevant controlling software.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] This practice is common for, as a main example, reading the contents of older video game console cartridges.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] Another example is making backups of firmware/OS ROMs from older computers or other devices - for archival purposes, as in many cases, the original chips are PROMs and thus at risk of exceeding their usable data lifetime.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The resultant memory dump files are known as **ROM images** or abbreviated *ROMs*, and can be used to produce duplicate ROMs - for example to produce new cartridges or as digital files for playing in console emulators.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The term *ROM image* originated when most console games were distributed on cartridges containing ROM chips, but achieved such widespread usage that it is still applied to images of newer games distributed on CD-ROMs or other optical media.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] ROM images of commercial games, firmware, etc. usually contain copyrighted software.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] The unauthorized copying and distribution of copyrighted software is a violation of copyright laws in many jurisdictions, although duplication for backup purposes may be considered fair use depending on location.
[src:dm-verity/read-only-memory] In any case, there is a thriving community engaged in the distribution and trading of such software for preservation/sharing purposes.
